Emeritus professor '''Brian Stoddart''' is an [[Australia]]n academic who was the [[Chancellor (education)|vice-chancellor]] of [[La Trobe University]] between 2005 and 2006.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rood |first=David |date=24 December 2005 |title=La Trobe 'flatline' has to go: new chief |url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/national/la-trobe-flatline-has-to-go-new-chief/2005/12/23/1135032184015.html |work=The Age |location=Melbourne |access-date=28 August 2018 }}</ref>  He is a well-known commentator on sporting matters, being involved in the foundation of the [[Australian Institute of Sport]]<ref>{{cite news |last=Fickling |first=David |date=24 February 2003 |title=Sea change |url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2003/feb/24/sportsscience.davidfickling |work=The Guardian |location=London |access-date=28 August 2018 }}</ref> and being the author of many books exploring the history and importance of sports in society.<ref>[http://catalogue.nla.gov.au/Search/Home?lookfor=author:%22Stoddart,%20Brian%22&iknowwhatimean=1 Book catalogue]</ref>

Australian sport had to hit rock bottom before opting for an academic route to world success. David Fickling charts the rise of a vibrant sports education section and meets two UK students studying sport in Queensland

