{{synthesis|date=November 2016}} [[File:William III Landing at Brixham, Torbay, 5 November 1688.jpg|right|thumb|William of Orange landing at Torbay in 1688]] This is a list of the members of the British nobility and gentry, who in 1688 deserted [[James II of England|King James II]] and pledged their allegiances to [[William III of England|Prince William of Orange]], as the events of the [[Glorious Revolution]] unfolded. *Admiral [[Matthew Aylmer, 1st Baron Aylmer|Matthew Aylmer]], who played a significant role in diverting the loyalty of the Royal Navy from King James to William of Orange. *Colonel [[Berkeley family|Berkley]], possibly ''Lord Fitzharding''.{{Clarify|date=July 2010}} *[[Henry Bertie (of Weston-on-the-Green)|Captain Henry Bertie]] (died 1743), brother of the [[Earl of Abingdon]]. *Squire Bray{{Clarify|date=July 2010}} *[[Henry Booth, 1st Earl of Warrington|Henry Booth, 2nd Baron Delamere]], took arms in Cheshire on November 1688, appearing in Manchester with 50 armed and mounted men, which had trebled before reaching Bowden Downs. *[[James Butler, 2nd Duke of Ormonde]] *[[William Cavendish, 1st Duke of Devonshire|William Cavendish, 4th Earl of Devonshire]], appeared in arms at Derby, proceeded to Nottingham, which soon became the headquarters of the Northern insurrection. *[[John Cecil, 5th Earl of Exeter]] *[[Hugh Cholmondeley, 1st Earl of Cholmondeley|Hugh Cholmondeley, 2nd Viscount Cholmondeley]], joined the northern insurrection at Nottingham in 1688, created Baron in 1689 and Earl in 1706. *Charles Cokayne, 3rd [[Viscount Cullen]] (died 30 December 1688) *Squire Coote{{Clarify|date=July 2010}} *[[George Compton, 4th Earl of Northampton]] *[[Henry Compton (bishop)|Henry Compton]], youngest son of the 2nd Earl of Northampton, Bishop of London, P.C. *[[George Churchill (Royal Navy officer)|George Churchill]] (1653–1710), brother of John Churchill and captain at sea, afterwards admiral. *[[John Churchill, 1st Duke of Marlborough|John Churchill, Baron Churchill of Sandridge]] (1650–1722), deserted on 25 Nov 1688, arguably "the death-blow for the Royal Cause".{{Citation needed|date=July 2010}} Afterwards created [[Duke of Marlborough (title)|Earl and later Duke of Marlborough]] and captain-general. *Sir Richard Dutton, or possibly Sir Ralph Dutton, MP for Gloucester *[[Thomas Fairfax, 5th Lord Fairfax of Cameron]], MP for York. *[[Charles Fane, 3rd Earl of Westmorland]] *[[Henry FitzRoy, 1st Duke of Grafton]], the first who on 24 November 1688 deserted the King's camp, accompanied by John Churchill. *[[Charles Gerard, 1st Earl of Macclesfield]], an "ancient Cavalier who had fought for Charles I, and had shared the exile of Charles II", assembled with William at the Hague in 1688. *[[John Granville, 1st Earl of Bath]], placed the fortress at Plymouth, which he commanded, at William's disposal on 18 November 1688, when William had arrived at Exeter. "The invaders therefore had now not a single enemy in their rear."<ref>{{cite book |last=Macaulay |first=Thomas Babington |authorlink=Thomas Babington Macaulay |title=The History of England from the Accession of James II |location=Philadelphia |publisher=J. B. Lippincott |year=1878 |volume=II |page=397 |chapter=Chapter IX |chapterurl=http://www.gutenberg.org/files/2439/2439-h/2439-h.htm#linknoteref-532 |accessdate=1 November 2016}}</ref> *[[Thomas Grey, 2nd Earl of Stamford]] *Captain Griffith{{Clarify|date=July 2010}} *Sir John Guise, Baronet (died 1695), MP for Gloucester *Henry Hamilton-Moore, 3rd [[Earl of Drogheda]] *[[Edward Harley (Parliamentarian)|Sir Edward Harley, Baronet]], in November 1688 took up arms in Worcestershire on behalf of the Prince of Orange. *[[Arthur Herbert, 1st Earl of Torrington|Arthur Herbert]], [[vice admiral]], created Earl of Torrington in 1689. *Henry Herbert, 4th [[Baron Herbert of Chirbury|Baron Herbert of Cherbury]], in November 1688 took up arms in Worcestershire on behalf of the Prince of Orange. *[[Henry Howard, 7th Duke of Norfolk]], with 300 armed and mounted men, in November 1688 appeared in the market place of Norwich, where he was joined by the mayor and alderman. *[[Edward Hyde, 3rd Earl of Clarendon|Edward Hyde, Lord Cornbury]] (1661–1723), son of the Earl of Clarendon and one of the first royal commanders to desert. He was the senior officer at Salisbury and deserted with as many troops as he could induce to follow him. *[[Henry Hyde, 2nd Earl of Clarendon]] (1638–1709), father of Lord Cornbury *[[Robert Leke, 3rd Earl of Scarsdale]] *[[John Lovelace, 3rd Baron Lovelace]], set out for Exeter to join the Prince of Orange, but was taken prisoner at Gloucester. *[[Richard Lumley, 1st Earl of Scarbrough|Richard Lumley]] seized Newcastle for William, created Viscount Lumley in 1689 and Earl of Scarborough in 1690. *[[John Manners, 1st Duke of Rutland|John Manners, 9th Earl of Rutland]] *Squire Marle{{Clarify|date=July 2010}} *[[Charles Montagu, 1st Duke of Manchester|Charles Montagu, 4th Earl of Manchester]], moved to Nottingham and was joined by Lord Cholmondeley and by Lord Grey de Ruthyn. *Edward Osborne, Viscount Latimer (died 1689), son the Earl of Danby. *[[Peregrine Osborne, 2nd Duke of Leeds|Peregrine Osborne, Lord Dunblane]], son the Earl of Danby. *[[Thomas Osborne, 1st Duke of Leeds|Thomas Osborne, 1st Earl of Danby]] (1631–1712), seized York for William, was created Duke of Leeds in 1694. *[[James Paynter (Jacobite)|James Paynter]], tried for and later acquitted of treason in Cornwall. *Sir Robert Peyton, Baronet (died 1689), colonel in the Dutch invasion *[[Charles Paulet, 2nd Duke of Bolton|Charles Powlett, Earl of Wiltshire]] *[[Charles Bodvile Robartes, 2nd Earl of Radnor]] *[[Richard Savage, 4th Earl Rivers|Richard Savage, Lord Colchester]], son of Earl Rivers *[[Charles Seymour, 6th Duke of Somerset]] *[[Robert Shirley, 1st Earl Ferrers|Robert Shirley, Lord Ferrers of Chartley]] *[[Philip Stanhope, 2nd Earl of Chesterfield]] *[[Charles Talbot, 1st Duke of Shrewsbury|Charles Talbot, 12th Earl of Shrewsbury]] *Squire Tibbing, probably [[Sir Thomas Tipping, 1st Baronet|Squire Thomas Tipping]] (1653–1718), former MP for Oxfordshire who had fled to the Netherlands due to a scandal *Sir John Trelawney, possibly [[Sir Jonathan Trelawny, 3rd Baronet]] *Squire Trenchard (1635–1713), possibly William Trenchard of Cutteridge, Wiltshire *Henry Yelverton, 15th [[Baron Grey of Ruthyn|Baron Grey de Ruthyn]], joined the Northern insurrection in 1688, created [[Viscount de Longueville]] in 1690.
